				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Wed, 01 Nov 2017 17:32:23 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>TL333s</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>1304786</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>I think that's intentional.</p> <p>Like, I noticed the same thing, that popular pseudoscience creeping in, but when you look at the interview, and the guy who's -1 seems perfectly normal and the researcher isn't, you have to think something has happened to shut down parts of the brain of the people in this Site, or else it's taking place in another universe where that's true. Either is kind of frightening.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-4130249#post-3624170</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-4130249/scp-3733#post-3624170</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Wed, 01 Nov 2017 16:52:05 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>Prosopagnostic</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>2794104</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>Excellent subtle horror. However, you're article strikes at a pet peeve of mine which prevents me from bestowing a +1.</p> <p>To explain: &quot;SCP-3733 activates several typically inactive areas of the brain&quot; - yeah those &quot;inactive areas&quot; don't exist. This seems to be a form of the common misconception of &quot;humans only have access to xx% of their brain's processing power&quot;, which originated in the long game of telephone that is science reporting and has next to no basis in actual neuroscience. Most readers probably won't notice or care about this, and I fully admit this is a minor nitpick of an otherwise excellent piece.</p> <p>(To explain why this gets under my skin so mych - I hold an MS in cognition &amp; neuroscience and am working towards a PhD in this same area, and I've lost count of all the times someone has asked me about &quot;using 100% of the brain&quot; or some such).</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
